default&#xa0;
default1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA strong, stable and long-term carbon price would provide an efficient long-term signal across the economy for investment in low-carbon innovation
default, leading to the achievement of carbon targets at lea
defaultst cost
default. However, this economically efficient outcome is in practice not achievable, because a) the long-term credibility of such a carbon price is very difficult—if not impossible—to achieve, since current parliaments cannot bind the hands of future legis
defaultlators
default, legally binding targets notwithstanding
default; b) an international carbon price would be required to embed this price signal throughout all products and services, and c) there are many market and system failures within innovation systems that 
defaultprevent eff
defaulticient
default responses to price signals, and which may block low-carbon innovation even where it is economically rational. 
defaultEffective innovation policy must engage with that complex reality. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe government
default’
defaults active approach to innovation policy
default, set out in the 
defaultBIS 
defaultInnovation and Research Strategy for Growth 
defaultis therefore very 
defaultwelcome
default, as it recognises the complexity of innovation and innovation policy
default. The recent development of industrial strategies in particular represents a 
defaultsensible 
defaultpragmatic break from years o
defaultf polarised debate between ‘laissez faire’ and ‘picking winners’; it recognises that government is an inevitable player within the innovation system, and that intelligent strategic engagement and support is the best approach. 
default&#xa0;
default1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, there are a number 
defaultof shortcomings to the 
defaultgovernment’s 
defaultapproach
default to low carbon innovation
default. 
defaultIn particular, o
defaultverall public funding for energy 
defaultRD&amp;D 
defaultremains low compared to many competitors. There is a case for increasing the overall level of funding support. In particular, there
default is a case for providing more long-term forms of finance
default. 
defaultThe UK 
defaultlow-carbon sector 
defaultdoes relatively well at attracting venture capital, second only to the US among major economies in terms of clean energy VC per unit GDP
default (according to data from Bloomberg Ne
defaultw Energy Finance)
default; but there is a dearth of longer-term supporting finance for em
defaulterging low-carbon technologies.
