default1.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is also a problem with strategic co-ordination. 
defaultThe failure to join up 
defaultlow carbon R&amp;D 
defaultpolicy and deployment policy with sufficient credi
defaultbility is undermining the UK’s ability to 
defaultattract investment in manufacturing 
defaultand R&amp;D 
defaultcapacity for key technologies, such as offshore wind. 
defaultThe continued uncertainty over mid-term carbon targets (particularly in the power sector) and renewable energy commi
defaulttments will raise costs of ultimately meeting targets, and will reduce the chance of the UK benefitting from the associated manufacturing and export opportunities. 
defaultPart of the problem is the political challenge of achieving alignment on key issues around d
defaultecarbonisation policy. But a second part of the problem is the lack of a strategic co-ordination mechanism for low-carbon innovation. LCICG, while a welcome development, has not been designed for an overall strategic co-ordination mission, nor has it been 
defaultresourced to meet such a mission. 
