default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLCICG has been an important development in enabling government to co-ordinate 
defaultR&amp;D spending on low-carbon technologies
default. However, 
defaultLCICG 
defaultdoes not meet t
defaulthe need for strategic co-ordination of low-carbon innovation policy identified by the CCC and others. LCICG’s remit is narrow, focused on improving the co-ordination of 
defaultpublic spending
default on 
defaulttechnologies
default. 
defaultThis had been missing, and LCICG has been useful in ov
defaultercoming that lack. 
defaultHowever, this focus on spending on technologies is only one part of innovation policy, which requires management and co-ordination not only of government-funded R&amp;D programmes, but also of the demand-side and enabling activities.  
default&#xa0;
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA g
defaultrouping that could co-ordinate and strategically develop low-carbon innovation policy might be expected to also have representation from
default, for example,
default the Government Procurement Service (given evidence that well-designed public procurement policies can sti
defaultmulate ‘mission-driven’ innovation) and from the Green Investment Bank. Similarly
default, it seems unfortunate that the LCICG does not explicitly aim to co-ordinate R&amp;D funding with efforts to remove market or regulatory barriers to low-carbon technologies, or ef
defaultforts to stimulate markets for low-carbon technologies, such as the various subsidy schemes
default.
